From experience, I can say I truly lucked out with how good Eat At State | Michigan State University is. Visiting other schools, I found that they weren't nearly as diverse and accommodating to different dietary restrictions as MSU. 

Since recently moving off campus, I'm realizing how nice it was to have ready-made meals available to me until midnight every day. Now that I'm preparing my own meals, I especially miss the Gallery, my favorite cafeteria on campus, located in Snyder-Phillips. Those sugar cookies on football game days? Mine don't turn out nearly as well!

-Claire, Class of 2016

MSU can be an intimidatingly large campus when you first arrive as a new student. With a contiguous area of 5,200 acres, getting around on campus seems like a daunting feat. But, as I, and many other students have come to realize, the size of the campus offers a great opportunity to explore and enjoy Michigan's natural beauty. 

I have come to really look forward to my daily bike rides to and from work and class. Not only are my rides eco-friendly, but they help me get a daily workout into my busy schedule. Students taking advantage of the bus system, walking and biking live out the university's goal to Be Spartan Green! I am proud to be one of them.

-Claire, Class of 2015

status_message:
Growing up in East Lansing, I remember seeing graduating MSU students taking photos by Sparty and thinking how accomplished and grown up they looked. I couldn't wait to be one of them someday. Now that I'm in their shoes, I can't believe how fast time flies.

It's so funny to think about the nervous, wide-eyed person I was when I came to MSU as a freshman and the slightly calmer person I am now. I've learned so much, both in my classes and outside of them, about myself and the alumna I want to be.  

From the lifelong friends I made, crises I endured, and life-changing experiences I had, it's safe to say MSU shaped me into the person who's going to walk across that stage. I will carry the lessons I learned at this university with me every day.  

I can't even begin to thank this university for all it has given me. In return, I'll do my best to make Sparty proud in the real world. Go Green!

-Lilly, Class of 2014

status_message:
What was your most memorable year at MSU?

At the end of each academic year, I like to write a summary about what I accomplished and what I participated in that year. Not only is it a way for me to reflect back on the year, but it's a good reference to have in the future if I'm trying to remember just exactly what I spent my four years at Michigan State doing. (A lot!)

This year, I have so much to write about, it feels like I'm giving myself a class assignment. Michigan State is full of opportunities, and I am taking advantage of many of them. From participating in Inside Out, to acting as a research assistant, to going to (almost) every football game, in my sophomore year, I've started to really delve into what makes MSU so great. 

-Claire, Class of 2016

status_message:
Do you keep in touch with your college roommates?

Living with five other girls during my senior year of college has turned out to be the perfect way to end my undergrad experience. It's crazy to think that, in a few weeks, I won't wake up and see them, and the city I grew up in, every day. 

From Bachelor Mondays and venting with my roommates to being an expert on this city, living in East Lansing has been the best experience a college girl could ask for. 

As bittersweet as moving away will be, I'm so glad that my last living experience here was such a great one. I will always think back with a smile on the memories that my roommates and I made in our house, and I hope we keep in touch in the years to come. 

-Lilly, Class of 2014

When I received an email about the MSU President's Report, I wasn't sure about applying to be part of it. I was wary of potentially getting myself into something I wouldn't want to do. Thankfully, my mom convinced me not to pass up such a great opportunity. 

By being a part of Inside Out, I've not only met eight other awesome students on MSU's campus, but I've gotten the chance to really learn about what's important to them and what makes each of them unique. 

Through the President's Report, I've also had the opportunity to talk about what's important to me in my college experience at Michigan State and share it with the entire MSU communityâ€”and the rest of the world! 

What's one thing that you want everyone to know about your MSU experience? 

-Claire, Class of 2016

As I mentioned previously, one of the reasons I came to MSU was because of its excellent study abroad program. Now that the time has come for me to start thinking about where I want to go, I'm grateful for all the help available to me. 

I've chosen to (hopefully!) study at Lancaster University in the United Kingdom. Seeing as I never pursued learning an additional language, the U.K. seems like a good fit for me. Also, the university itself is in a great location, near the city, coast and countryside. 

On another note, I can't wait to meet more people in my Doctor Who fandom! 

MSU has so many opportunities to customize your study abroad experience, and by choosing my location, I am one step closer to becoming a world traveler.

Spartans, have you studied abroad in the U.K.? What about elsewhere in the world? 

-Claire, Class of 2016

status_message:
MSU Residential College in the Arts and Humanities began in 2005 as an innovative living-learning degree option for students. Though it is a new program, it's already well loved, especially by me.

When applying for schools, MSU was one of my first options, but I was intimidated by its size. RCAH gave me the opportunity to go to MSU and have all of the advantages of a major university, like awesome study abroad opportunities and sporting events, but still get the feel of a smaller college. 

Through the residential college, my passion for civic engagement has been supported and has had the chance to thrive. I have so many people to thank for my great learning experience at MSU. First in this line is Dean Esquith for creating the environment that I love to live and learn in. 

Who would you like to thank for making your MSU experience awesome?

-Claire, Class of 2016

When people ask me for reasons they should go to Michigan State, a lot of things come to mind. We're great for study abroad. We do awesome research. We have a beautiful campus. The list goes on. 

One of the other things I never forget to say is that we make our own ice cream, and it's the best I've ever had. 

This year, I've become attached to the new Peppermint Stick flavor. Regardless of flavor or season, though, whenever I'm at the Union, I always feel pulled to go and grab a cone at the MSU Dairy Store. Usually, I don't resist that feeling.

What do you love about MSU? 

-Claire, Class of 2016

In high school, I was never really involved with theatre. This is why when my friend asked me if I wanted to go check out the Roial Improv team with her, I was a little hesitant. One semester and several shows later, I've fallen in love with improvisational comedy. 

This semester, I even had the opportunity to travel with the team to Indianapolis to take part in the College Improv Tournament. We got 22 minutes to perform in front of an audience and three judges at a comedy club in the city. We didn't win, but I already know it's going to be one of my favorite memories from being here at Michigan State. 

What was something you decided to take a risk and try while at MSU? 

-Claire, Class of 2016

Although I've taken a handful of art classes during my college career, I took my first graphic design class last semester and fell in love with everything about it. 

I wanted to learn more about it, so when it came time to make my schedule for my final semester at MSU, I scoured Schedule Builder for graphic design classes. When I found one completely about typography and fonts, I instantly enrolled. 

In this class, we get to design our own typeface, and I've already learned more information about fonts than I thought existed. Needless to say, I love it!

Have you ever been surprised by a class like this? 

-Lilly, Class of 2014

MSU had a fantastic year. How would you describe 2013 in one word?

MSU continues to change the game on and off the field by creating opportunity for students all over the globe. Now it's your turn. 

Join fellow Spartans as we gather 100 donations to make a brighter future for students. http://givingto.msu.edu/promise/

As a senior, I've done a lot of reflecting on my experience here at MSU. In my ponderings, I've realized that there are a few must-do things I've left unchecked in my undergraduate career. That's why my New Year's resolutions for this year will be completed mostly during my final semester. Nothing like leaving it to the last minute, right? 

Here are some of the things I'd like to do:
Wait in line for front row seats for a big game
Kiss the "S" in the middle of the Breslin Center court
Play in an IM game
Get a photo with Sparty as a graduate
Take a canoe down the Red Cedar
Have a picnic in the Children's Garden
Perform in a slam poetry tournament
Try every flavor at the MSU Dairy Store

Can you think of anything I forgot?

-Lilly, Class of 2014

status_message:
Although the last couple weeks of the semester can be stressful for college students, there is a light at the end of the tunnel: going home for winter break. 

While most of my friends leave East Lansing to go home, I pack up my car and drive a few blocks. Even though I'm from East Lansing, it doesn't make going home any less awesome for me. Nothing beats the feeling of curling up on the comfy couch in my living room, watching Christmas movies with my family, and eating their delicious (and free) food. 

No matter where I wind up living, there will always be something wonderful about going home that makes my holiday season more special than any other. 

What are your plans this holiday season?

-Lilly, Class of 2014

Finals week is always hailed as the most stressful for students everywhere. In my experience as a journalism student, though, the final push to get everything done strikes the week before finals. 

This means a lot of late nights spent in MSU College of Communication Arts & Sciences, a lot of coffee, and a lot of pizza delivery. Luckily, my professors provided the latter for us during yesterday's late work night with my JRN 400 class.

Although the end of the semester can be a challenge, I know I'll always look back on the late nights and hard work with a smile. As silly as it sounds, these all-nighters have been some of my favorite nights on campus. 

Good luck on your final exams, Spartans!

-Lilly, Class of 2014

I'm so thankful to forever call myself a Spartan. 

Every time I pass Sparty, I can't help but think about how incredibly lucky I am to be a member of a worldwide family who does awe-inspiring things every day. 

I'm thankful to have such a wide variety of classes and majors to choose from, which will prepare me to be an inspiring alumna myself this coming springâ€”as hard as that will be.

Every Saturday, I'm thankful to be a part of Spartan Nation, thousands strong, cheering on MSU, no matter the weather. 

I'm thankful to have thousands of fellow students to put my arms around when I hear the first notes of the MSU alma materâ€”and for the immense pride I will always feel when I hear that song. 

I'm thankful for Sparty and his one-armed pushups and for the goosebumps the Spartan Marching Band gives me when it plays the best fight song there is. 

I'm thankful for green, and I'm thankful for white. I'm thankful for all opportunities these colors always will give me. 

-Lilly, Class of 2014

Every other year, my family and I follow Spartan football down to Chicago to watch the team take on the Northwestern Wildcats. 

Not only do I get to take in an extra football game, (score!) but I also get to spend some much-needed time with my sister, Katy, who lives in Chicago. I don't get to see her very often, so this trip has become one of my favorite family traditions.  

The atmosphere at Ryan Field is awesome, too. Even though it's an away game, the huge number of Spartans who make the 242-mile trip make it seem like we never left Spartan Stadium. Go Green! 

-Lilly, Class of 2014

What do you love most about MSU in winter? 

-Lilly, Class of 2014

In my School of Journalism at Michigan State University  capstone class, we're split up into teams, and each team has to create a different product. My team is developing an iPad magazine that will be available for download in the iTunes Store by the end of the semester. Pretty cool, right? 

Most employers are looking to hire people familiar with changing technology, so classes like this one make me feel more prepared to start applying for jobs. We even got to test out Google Glass, one of the newest technologies out there! 

It's interesting to look back on how my classes have evolved during my four years here at MSU. As a senior, my classes focus on things that I'm interested in and perfect skills that will be useful in a post-graduation career. 

-Lilly, Class of 2014

Each year, MSU hosts a variety of Homecoming festivities, and, as a senior, I wanted to take part in as much as I could. I got to experience this year's game, parade, and hayride with some of my best friends and family, and I wouldn't have had it any other way. 

Reuniting and celebrating MSU with Spartans new and old is one of my favorite parts of Homecoming. The atmosphere on campus is so exciting during this time of year; you can practically feel the energy buzzing through the air. 

I still can't believe that I'll be celebrating Homecoming as an alumna next year. It's nice to know that no matter what year you graduated, you're always a member of the Spartan family. Go Green!

-Lilly, Class of 2014

I remember walking into Jenison Fieldhouse for the first time as a little girl attending the MSU Women's Basketball summer camp. Back then, I thought it was just a big, old gym. 

Now, after hearing all the history that surrounds that big, old gym, I can't help but get goosebumps knowing I learned how to make a lay-up on the same court that Magic Johnson played on. 

Although Spartan basketball no longer calls it home, Jenison will always be home to so many legendary players and moments. I wish I had a time machine, so I could go back and witness all of them. 

-Lilly, Class of 2014

As nerdy as this may sound, some of my favorite Spartan memories happened in this building: MSU Main Library. I've spent countless hours studying here, but I also associate the library with smiles and laughter.

My friends and I holing up in the library have turned into great nights. We wear our comfiest clothes and even order pizza. I mean, who can be productive on an empty stomach, right? 

While some nights are more productive than others, I know I'll never forget staying up and bonding with some of my best friends, just as so many Spartans before me have done.

-Lilly, Class of 2014

status_message:
Of all the selfies I've taken on my iPhone, I have to say this one is my personal favorite.

First, some background: When the South Florida football game was delayed, Coach Izzo promised the reluctant student section that he would watch part of the game with us after evacuation. 

Later, when I saw him taking in the game a few rows behind me, I couldn't help but run over and snag a photo. Seeing Coach Izzo, who is such an important figure in the MSU community, sit among thousands of students has to be one of my favorite Spartan moments thus far. 

By keeping his promise, it shows how much he values and appreciates us, in or out of Breslin. It's nice to know we have a down-to-earth (and not to mention photogenic) coach who's willing to do whatever it takes to ensure the safety of his biggest fans. 

-Lilly, Class of 2014

As a college student, moving into new place every August is a back-to-school ritual. However, this August was a little different for me than previous ones. This year, I moved into a six-person house with some of my closest friends. 

For the first time in my college career, I don't have to climb a ladder to get to my bed, which I'm still getting used to. I also have my own room to come home to every day. I can't think of a better way or a better group people to spend my last year at MSU with, and I can't wait to see what memories the six of us make in this house.

-Lilly, Class of 2014

When I walked into the Eli and Edythe Broad Art Museum at MSU for the first time, my jaw dropped. The colorful exhibits mixed with the angular architecture of the building make for an truly visual experience, not to mention the perfect escape on a rainy summer day.

While preparing for a swim across the English Channel, MSU alumna Amanda Mercer was diagnosed with breast cancer. Despite her doctors' doubts, she powered through. She and her teammates ended up setting a world record and meeting their fundraising goal for ALS.

"Everything that I had dreamed of and hoped for didn't get derailed just because I got a cancer diagnosis," says Mercer. "That's pretty amazing."

status_message:
When the South Pointe cafeteria opened in Case Hall, my friends and I were excited for its debut. The first day it was open, the seven of us walked over there after classes all the way from West Circle. The cafeteria's decor is amazing, and not that I start with dessert, but I can never resist the delicious crepes that are served.

By now, I've eaten at every cafeteria on MSU's campus, and there is something special about each one. Each holds a memory for me. It's pretty cool to think that I was at South Pointe's opening, though, as it will no doubt be a part of so many Spartans' lives. 

Which cafeteria is your favorite?

Whenever I walk past the Hannah statue on campus, I think about my dad's MSU stories. He was a student when Hannah was president. My dad has stories of residence hall shenanigans, playing billiards in the MSU Union, and even seeing the football team win a Rose Bowl. 

After hearing his stories, it was impossible for me to want to go anywhere else. I wanted to make MSU my home like it is for him. I can't wait to someday tell my own family about the memories I made at MSU in my four years. 

-Lilly, Class of 2014

I've experienced a range of majors during my undergraduate years. While I was an art major, I spent most of my time in the Kresge Art Center. Now every time I pass it, tons of memories come to mind. From pulling all-nighters in the studio with my classmates to the nerves that I experienced before my first critique, these memories are some of the best of my college experience so far.

status_message:
Over the past six weeks, I've gotten so used to this view. Seeing East Lansing, the place where I've lived for 20 years, will seem new again in just a few days. 

As I start packing, it's hard to believe that I'll be trading the Arno River for the Red Cedar, cobblestone for pavement, and gelato for Ben and Jerry's. But really, all I'm doing is trading one home for a different one. 

I'm so lucky that I can come back to Florence someday and show my family the home that I made here. I know this place will always have a special place in both my memories and my heart. 

-Lilly, Class of 2014

Choosing where to spend my last weekend in Italy was not an easy task. After dreaming of visiting the country for years, I wanted to make the right choice before packing up and heading back to East Lansing. After much deliberation, I chose Milan, and knew instantly I made the right choice. 

My friend Colleen and I went together and were given a personal tour of the city by a friend of hers who lives nearby. We saw all of the classic sights, such as the Duomo, but also some beautiful quiet parts of the city that I never would have found on my own. Not only am I happy I went to Milan, but my closet is, too.

-Lilly, Class of 2014

As a part of the Italian study abroad experience, our professor scheduled a trip to Modena, a town known for its parmigiano reggiano cheese. There, we toured a cheese factory. Getting to know my host family has been one of my favorite parts of my study abroad experience. I'm not only learning the Italian language from them, I bond with them and hear their experiences every night over pasta. The automatic in to the princess party wasn't so bad, either.

-Lilly, Class of 2014

One of my favorite parts about Rome is the presence of ruins throughout the city. I love when old buildings and new ones are mixed within a city (or campus, just like a certain one that I'm partial to in East Lansing). Rome takes this concept to another level with its ruins, throwing ancient history in the middle of all the roads and Segway tours.  

I only got to visit Rome for a day on my study abroad trip, but in that day, I saw the Vatican, Colosseum and Trevi Fountain. I also ran into a Spartan alumnus! Now I can officially say I've yelled "Go Green!" across the world.  

-Lilly, Class of 2014

While sending out alert notifications concerning the severe weather on May 28, the emergency system MSU Police uses inadvertently sent an email message to some members of the MSU community about an active shooter on campus. There was not a shooting incident on campus.

I have always dreamed of visiting Italy, and this summer, I finally find myself here. I'm studying Italian language and history in Florence for six weeks with 14 fellow Spartans. Here I am (back row, in white) with my classmates in la Piazza de Vecchio. 

Who knew that studying isn't so hard when you're surrounded by what you're learning every day? It's awesome to hear my host family, including my adorable 2-year-old Italian brother Brando, speaking the language fluently and trying to pick up on what they're discussing. (Even if it's usually what Brando's trying to put in his mouth at the moment.) 

If you could travel anywhere in the world, where would it be?

-Lilly, Class of 2014

Getting sick when you're away from your family for the first time can be really scary. This happened to me in the spring semester of my freshman year. I had a pretty terrible sinus infection and lost my voice for about a week.

I was away at college and didn't really know what to do. I didn't have time to visit my family doctor, but I knew there was place I could go called the Olin Health Center. I set up an appointment, met with a nurse practitioner, was prescribed some medication, and I slowly started to get better.

The staff members at Olin were great, and it was really reassuring to know that there was somewhere on campus I could go to be taken care of and treated. 

-Jeffrey, class of 2013

When I lived in Gilchrist Hall, most of my weeknights were spent in the downstairs study lounge. My favorite spot was a table near the window in the sun room, and I'd often stay there until nearly 2 a.m. working on homework. One thing that always calmed me down was listening for a train whistle as a train rushed through campus. It amazed me that I could hear it, even though I lived pretty far from the tracks. No matter what I was working on or how stressed out I was, I stopped what I was doing to listen to the train pass by. 

Even when I'm not in East Lansing, I always think of MSU and those long nights in the Gilchrist study lounge when I hear a train whistle.

-Annie, class of 2013

Starting off my freshman year I was determined to walk or ride my bike to wherever I needed to go on campus. No warm bus rides for me. I was going to get through college without having to buy a bus pass.

Four years later, I look back and laugh at how hard headed I was. To this day I still haven't bought a bus pass or taken the bus to class, but that's just because I'm so used to walking and biking all of the time. 

Every time I see a bus I'm reminded of my decision and all of the rain, snow, and sleet I've walked and biked through. Maybe I should have gotten a bus pass after all...

-Jeffrey, class of 2013

Will Detroit's woes spur a creative resurgence, just like the struggles of 1920s Harlem did? Check out the play this weekend!
Read more here: http://bit.ly/ZKAI6V

During fall semester of my freshman year, I was enrolled in a class in Conrad Hall, which was clear across campus from my dorm in Brody. I had no idea how long it would take for me to walk to class on the first day, so I played it safeâ€”and gave myself a full hour and a half to get there. I ended up being nearly 45 minutes early and had no idea what to do with myself. I felt lost and confused, which is how I spent a good part of that first week of classes.

As I think back to how I felt when I first came to MSU, it's amazing to see how much I've grown and changed in my four years here.  And, as a graduating senior, I finally know how long to give myself to get to class.

-Annie, class of 2013

Cook Hall, pictured in 1868, was the first laboratory used exclusively for agricultural research on campus. Now, Cook Hall is home to the Department of Agricultural Economics. status_message:
This semester I had the chance to check out a performance by Rebecca Kling, a transgender performance artist based in Chicago, IL. I felt really inspired by her work, which tells her story of dealing with transphobic behavior and uses it as a way to educate others, as well as show other trans people that they are not alone in their struggles. To find out more about her and her work, I asked Rebecca to sit down for an interview with me for a series of videos I'm producing as part of my senior thesis, and she agreed!

I'm personally very thankful that MSU strives to bring performances and other programs like this to our campus consistently. And, in being flexible in what kind of work I can do as I progress towards my degree, I'm able to find more ways to incorporate this into my education. It's certainly something unique about this campus, and makes me very glad to be a part of it. 

-Matt, Class of 2013

Jeffrey and I were walking back to work from the Union yesterday and took a detour to check out a bench next to the Music Building. The bench was in memory of Gerald "Gerry" Kirschner, who graduated from MSU in 1958 and was a charter member of the MSU Jewish Studies Advisory Board. When we first saw this bench, we thought it was just a place to sit during nice weather and catch up on reading, but it's more than that--it's a story. It's a part of MSU's history, a piece of someone's Spartan legacy. We don't know about you, but we love finding things on campus like this.

-Annie and Jeffrey, class of 2013

Whenever I see the Red Cedar River start to flood, I think about the first time I came to MSU after I had been accepted. I was visiting campus for a scholarship competition and was walking back to my friend's room in Snyder-Phillips from the Kellogg Center. Snow was melting and the river was starting to flood, and all I could think was how strange it was that this would be my home next year. Now, almost four years later, all I can think as I walk along the river is how strange it is that this won't be my home next year. Crazy how time flies, right?
 
-Annie, class of 2013

As a freshman, the first time I truly felt like I was in college was when I first walked to the library to study for an exam and heard Beaumont Tower chiming. I had been feeling homesick and lonely, but hearing Beaumont made me remember why I was so drawn to MSU when I was applying to colleges. At that moment, I felt at home.

I walked past Beaumont today and stopped for a moment to listen to the tower chime. Fall semester is ending faster than I'd like it to, which means my last semester as an undergrad is quickly approaching. During these next few months, I'm going to take the time to stop and enjoy the things I love about MSU.

-Annie, class of 2013

Sometimes I get so wrapped up in my day, I forget to take a look around and appreciate the little things. Today, I saw a few locks painted with hearts and initials locked to a bridge across the Red Cedar river while I was walking around, and it reminded me of something I had heard of before. There's a bridge over the Seine River in Paris, France where lovers write their names on padlocks, lock it to the bridge. Apparently, it's supposed to symbolize love that cannot be broken. Cool, right? It definitely brightened up my day.

Taylor, Class of 2013

President Simon spoke at an event last week acknowledging an academic collaboration between Michigan State University and Central Michigan University. MSU has invited three CMU assistant professors of physics to conduct research at our Facility for Rare Isotope Beams. During the event, President Simon chatted with Ian Davidson, dean of CMU's College of Science and Technology, as well as Matthew Redshaw, Kathrin Wimmer, and Georgios Perdikakisâ€”the three CMU assistant professors. She also shared a laugh with the FRIB laboratory director, Konrad Gelbke, before her speech.
 
In her remarks, President Simon noted that this partnership is a great example of "a way that we must work together as a sort of 'Team Michigan.'"
 
After the event, President Simon asked if I needed a quote or any other remarks from her. I said no and mentioned that her quote about "Team Michigan" was really awesome. She laughed, patted me on the arm, and said, "Well, I was trying to make your job a little easier today." If that didn't just make my day, I don't know what else could!
 
For more info on this partnership, go to: http://news.msu.edu/story/11380/
 
Go Green!
-Taylor, Class of 2013

"I am a proud Spartan and always will be," says alumnus Howard Leikert. "My Spartan Saga is not over. The education, experience, and friendships that I found at Michigan State will last me a lifetime."

With 50-plus years of engagement in Africa, Michigan State University is receiving $45 million in funding from The MasterCard Foundation to support 185 undergraduate and master's degree students throughout The MasterCard Foundation Scholars Program, which provides talented, yet financially disadvantaged youth â€“ especially those from Africa â€“ with access to high-quality education.

As the only institution in Michigan to join the program, MSU will host the most Scholars among the U.S. partner institutions, welcoming the first cohort of Scholars this fall with four graduate students and two undergraduates.

"Michigan State and The MasterCard Foundation both recognize that Africa is approaching an important inflection point," said MSU President Lou Anna K. Simon. "Africa now hosts seven of the world's ten fastest-growing national economies and is the world's youngest continent demographically. That offers remarkable potential for innovation, and the Scholars Program will add leverage by building Africa's educational capacity."
link_name: MSU, MasterCard partner on African scholars program

Monday, Sept. 17, 2012: Yesterday, I attended "East Lansing Welcomes the World," an annual event where MSU and the City of East Lansing community welcome our international students to the area. There were tons of students there along with MSU administrators and local leaders.

I listened as President Simon chatted with food science and economics sophomore Dominic Nangea (left) and premed sophomore Kuya Julius (right), both from Kenya. They showed off the sticks they were holding, which symbolize peace and leadership in their culture. Afterward, they told me how cool it was that the president came up and spoke with them and how they're looking forward to getting to know her.
 
Before President Simon delivered the opening address, I got a chance to talk with her about how cool this event is. She mentioned how we want our MSU students studying abroad to feel welcome in their new homes and how this event is "a way of doing that for our international studentsâ€”not only on campus but in our community."
 
I thought that was really something special. As Spartans, we welcome everyone with open arms. It's events like this that really separate us from everyone else.
 
â€“Go Green! Taylor, Class of 2013

The cars were aiding in the transport of Ransom E. Olds' personal vehicle, which was in a trailer nearby. Olds, founder of Oldsmobile in Lansing, donated his own personal 1903 Curved Dash Oldsmobile to Michigan State College in 1948. Michigan State University Museum is loaning the historic car for a special new exhibit being developed at the R.E. Olds Transportation Museum.

More information at http://bit.ly/PhFDZW.

MSU alumna Judi Brown Clarke, diversity director at MSU's BEACON Center, warns about overzealous Olympic parents.

Clarke received a silver medal in the 400-meter hurdles at the 1984 Los Angeles Olympics and then went on to coach at MSU. As an Olympian, she witnessed young athletes who fell apart as their controlling parents pushed them to the limit.

Monday, July 30, 2012: While sitting in on a meeting with President Simon and Lansing Mayor Virg Bernero, I got a taste of how diverse the president's responsibilities really are. The two talked about working together to connect Lansing, East Lansing, and other surrounding communities.
 
The discussion that stuck out the most to me was the idea to get the cities of Lansing and East Lansing more involved in welcoming Michigan State University's freshmen to the mid-Michigan region. The surrounding communities are so important to a lot of us here at MSU. I think getting the community more involved in welcoming our new Spartans would be an awesome way to start out the school year. 

What do you love most about the Spartan community?   
 
-Go Green! Taylor, Class of 2013

status_message:
On Tuesday morning, I got up bright and early, braved the scorching summer heat, and grabbed a front row seat at the 2012 Ag Expo opening breakfast. President Simon appeared up on stage with Michigan Governor Rick Snyder and alongside friends and colleagues in agriculture. She spoke a bit about the importance of agriculture at MSU to the state and to the country, and the importance of the fact that MSU has stayed true to its land-grant roots. As a third-generation Spartan, I've bled green all my life, and being a Spartan is really important to me. And because of this, I loved what she said and how she said it. Her words made me feel even more proud to go to a school that has stayed true to itself over the years.

President Simon was surprised when I said that I'd never been to the the Ag Expo before. I wish I would've visited in previous years-- it's a pretty big deal here at MSU! 

Today is the last day of MSU's 2012 Ag Expo. It runs from 9 a.m. to 3 p.m. and is located on campus off Mount Hope Road. If you've got time, go check it out! More info at http://agexpo.msu.edu/. 
 
-Go Green! Taylor, Class of 2013

A full-scale emergency exercise will take place today on MSU's main campus. During the exercise, first responders and other resources will be deployed as if an actual incident was occurring. Do not be alarmed.

Signs indicating police training will be in the area of the exercise. The exact location will not be announced in advance, but it will be in the east area of campus. The timing will be during normal business hours today.

This exercise will specifically prepare first responders, university administrators and other staff members in how to respond to emergencies.
link_name: Emergency exercise to take place today on MSU's campus

A gas leak has been reported at Michigan State University near the MSU Police Department on Red Cedar Road.

The front lot and public entrance to the police department is closed. Officials from the East Lansing Fire Department and Consumers Energy are responding to the situation.

All persons are asked to avoid that location. Visit msu.edu and police.msu.edu for further details.
